## Root cause

`z.<schema>().default(value)` was already designed to shallow-copy non-primitive default values on each parse (`packages/zod/src/v4/core/api.ts` calls `util.shallowClone(defaultValue)` in a getter, and there are existing tests asserting object/array defaults return a fresh copy each time). However, `util.shallowClone` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` only handled plain objects and arrays â€” for anything else (`Map`, `Set`, `Date`, etc.) it just returned the original reference:

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  return o;   // Map/Set/Date fall through here, same reference every time
}
```

That's exactly what the reporter observed: mutating the parsed `Map` mutated the schema's stored default, so the next `.parse(undefined)` returned the already-mutated instance.

## Fix

Extended `shallowClone` to also copy `Map`, `Set`, and `Date` instances (`packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts`):

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  if (o instanceof Map) return new Map(o);
  if (o instanceof Set) return new Set(o);
  if (o instanceof Date) return new Date(o.getTime());
  return o;
}
```

This is used by both v4 classic and v4 mini `_default`/`_prefault`, so both get the fix. I verified with a repro test (Map/Set/Date defaults no longer shared across parses) and ran the full `zod` package test suite â€” all 326 files / 3680 tests pass.

