## Root cause

In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/schemas.ts`, both `$ZodUnion` and `$ZodXor` initializers unconditionally read `def.options[0]._zod.run`:

```ts
const single = def.options.length === 1;
const first = def.options[0]._zod.run;
```

This line executes eagerly at schema construction (not lazily at parse time). When `options` is `[]`, `def.options[0]` is `undefined`, so `.run` throws `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'run')` as soon as `z.union([])` or `z.xor([])` is called.

## Fix

Only dereference `def.options[0]` when `single` is true (i.e., there's exactly one option to reach for):

```ts
const single = def.options.length === 1;
const first = single ? def.options[0]._zod.run : undefined;
...
if (single) {
  return first!(payload, ctx);
}
```

With zero options, the `for` loop over `def.options` never runs, so `results` stays empty and both `handleUnionResults`/`handleExclusiveUnionResults` correctly report an `invalid_union` failure â€” matching the type-level `never` semantics â€” instead of crashing.

Verified with a scratch test hitting `z.union([]).safeParse(1)` and `z.xor([]).safeParse(1)` (both now return `{ success: false }` instead of throwing), then ran the full zod test suite (3696 tests) with no regressions.

Root cause and fix:

`floatSafeRemainder` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` computed decimal-place counts by splitting `val.toString()`/`step.toString()` on `"."` and falling back to a scientific-notation regex only when that split gave `0`. But `(2.5e-7).toString()` is `"2.5e-7"`, whose split-on-`.` fraction is `"5e-7"` (length 4, non-zero) â€” so the fallback never engaged and it wildly undercounted actual decimal places (4 instead of 8), corrupting the `toFixed`-based integer comparison used to detect non-multiples.

Fix: replaced the ad-hoc split+conditional-regex logic with a single `decimalPlaceCount` helper that always properly parses scientific notation (mantissa fraction digits + exponent), applied uniformly to both `val` and `step`:

```ts
function decimalPlaceCount(numString: string): number {
  const match = numString.match(/^-?\d*\.?(\d*)e-(\d+)$/i);
  if (match) {
    return match[1].length + Number.parseInt(match[2], 10);
  }
  return (numString.split(".")[1] || "").length;
}
```

Verified: `multipleOf(1e-7)` now correctly rejects `2.5e-7`/`3.3e-7` and accepts `3e-7`, and the full test suite (322 files, 3656 tests) passes.
